<emphasis bold="true" box="[439,794,753,776]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
Key to Genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1886" box="[642,794,753,776]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ammophilini">Ammophilini</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" box="[163,655,812,834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">from BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976, slightly modified</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="386" pageId="2" pageNumber="385" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
1. Episternal sulcus curving back to scrobe from subalar fossa, then extending obliquely ventrad to anteroventral area of mesopleuron (
<figureCitation box="[772,831,871,893]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); New World forms .... ..................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="MENKE" authorityName="MENKE" box="[856,1070,897,918]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Eremnophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[856,988,897,918]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Eremnophila</emphasis>
MENKE
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
- Episternal sulcus extending straight down from subalar fossa (in some species absent), not passing through scrobe (
<figureCitation box="[572,633,955,977]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) ................................................................ 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">2 Claws in most specimens simple but if with single basal tooth on inner margin then mouthparts very long, galea attaining base of stipes when folded ...............................3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">- Claws with one or two basal teeth on inner margin; galea not extending beyond stipes midlength when folded and in most specimens shorter; Old World forms ........ 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
3. Apex of sternum I (petiole) meeting and in many specimens overlapping base of sternum II (
<figureCitation box="[330,396,1131,1153]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); spiracle of tergum I located before apex of sternum I (in profile); petiole in many specimens bent upward at level of base of tergum I.................... ....................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="FERNALD" authorityName="FERNALD" authorityYear="1927" box="[863,1070,1182,1203]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[863,968,1182,1203]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Podalonia</emphasis>
FERNALD
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
- Apex of sternum I not reaching base of sternum II, intervening space mostly long and consisting of membrane and ligament (
<figureCitation box="[647,711,1240,1262]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); spiracle of tergum I located at or beyond apex of sternum I; sternum I in many specimens bent downward or straight at level of base of tergum I............................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="W. KIRBY" authorityName="W. KIRBY" authorityYear="1798" box="[844,1070,1291,1312]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Ammophila" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="2" pageNumber="385" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[844,961,1291,1312]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Ammophila</emphasis>
W. KIRBY
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
4. Mesothoracic venter with anteromedian projection behind forecoxa; petiole socket nearly completely surrounded by propodeal tergum (
<figureCitation box="[739,802,1349,1371]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); inner orbits of female strongly converging below; midtibia with single spur .............. 
<taxonomicName authority="GRIBODO" authorityName="GRIBODO" box="[834,1071,1374,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Eremochares" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[834,969,1374,1395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Eremochares</emphasis>
GRIBODO
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[163,1071,812,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="385">
- Mesothoracic venter without anteromedian projection, at most obtusely angled (exception: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Beaumont" baseAuthorityYear="1956" box="[322,571,1433,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Parapsammophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foleyi">
<emphasis box="[322,571,1433,1454]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Parapsammophila foleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); petiole socket broadly bounded ventrally by T-shaped propodeal sternum (
<figureCitation box="[535,607,1458,1480]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="385">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); inner orbits of female only slightly converging below or parallel or diverging below; midtibia with two spurs (one may be reduced or absent) ........................................................................................... 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="386">
<paragraph blockId="3.[163,1070,200,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="386">
5. Foretarsomere I of female strongly asymmetrical, its outer apex prolonged (
<figureCitation box="[968,1031,200,222]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); free margin of male clypeus rounded or truncate; tarsi in most specimens with arolia; male gonostyle of usual shape ....................... 
<taxonomicName authority="TASCHENBERG" authorityName="TASCHENBERG" box="[728,1070,251,272]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Parapsammophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[728,915,251,272]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Parapsammophila</emphasis>
TASCHENBERG
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[163,1070,200,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="386">
- Foretarsomere I of female nearly symmetrical, outer apex only slightly produced (fig. 10); male clypeus triangular; arolia absent; male gonostyle of unusual shape (
<figureCitation box="[209,269,335,357]" captionStart="Figs 1-10" captionStartId="127.[163,203,1450,1470]" captionTargetBox="[193,1047,196,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-1@127.[185,1047,196,1438]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="Figs 1-10: (1) Eremnophila and (2) Ammophila: lateral view of anterior half of thorax (es = episternal sulcus); (3) Podalonia: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (4) Ammophila: gastral segments I-II lateral and ventral; (5) Parapsammophila and (6) Eremochares: posterior view of petiole socket, hindcoxa, and propodeal sternite (solid black); (7) lateral view of hindtarsal claw with basal tooth; (8) Hoplammophila: male genitalia; (9) Parapsammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (10) Hoplammophila: foretarsomere I of female; (BOHART &amp; MENKE 1976)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341136/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) ......................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="DE BEAUMONT" authorityName="DE BEAUMONT" box="[750,1070,335,356]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Hoplammophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="386" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[750,914,335,356]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="386">Hoplammophila</emphasis>
DE BEAUMONT
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
